1
00:00:01,030 --> 00:00:02,290
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:02,570 --> 00:00:11,830
In this video our talk will be about a homemade machine for winding multi-turn coils, of the Tesla transformer type.

3
00:00:12,550 --> 00:00:17,990
All who have ever wound them know what a laborious process this is and how much time it takes.

4
00:00:18,710 --> 00:00:31,690
For example, to wind such a Tesla on a 50 mm frame in terms of time, the work takes about an hour of intensive labor.

5
00:00:32,170 --> 00:00:38,610
Making it in manual mode is quite simple, because such a diameter easily fits in the hand.

6
00:00:39,170 --> 00:00:55,390
But when it comes to winding such coils — here the frame diameter is 153 mm — and besides if it's varnish-coated, doing this manually is already very problematic.

7
00:00:56,370 --> 00:01:02,690
I made this build in a couple of evenings, counting the time the glue dried.

8
00:01:04,210 --> 00:01:16,810
The machine itself is made from solid pine, width 20 cm, and the length from the front rack of the machine to the end of the lower guide is 80 cm.

9
00:01:16,810 --> 00:01:31,930
The front rack of the machine is fastened rigidly, and the rear rack can move along the lower guide — this way we can install frames of different lengths here.

10
00:01:31,930 --> 00:01:50,110
Here from the central hole to the base of the lower guide is 16 cm, which can let us install a coil about 30 cm in diameter for winding wire.

11
00:01:52,510 --> 00:02:00,340
The work on this build should start with being able to find some motor with a gearbox.

12
00:02:00,950 --> 00:02:07,510
In this case in my stocks I found this — can't say from what, sometime I bought it incidentally.

13
00:02:08,370 --> 00:02:19,430
The main moment here is the gear ratio — here it's 100 to 1, that is 100 motor revolutions correspond to 1 revolution of the central shaft.

14
00:02:19,430 --> 00:02:29,890
The motor here is DC and this is very good, since further you can do rotation regulation here.

15
00:02:30,330 --> 00:02:35,110
The minimum tool set for this build is a jigsaw.

16
00:02:36,550 --> 00:02:49,610
I advise applying small-tooth blades on the jigsaw for cutting — they suit very well for cutting plywood, but also the end cut comes out quite quality.

17
00:02:50,670 --> 00:02:58,110
Further this is a screwdriver, a set of bits and some set of drills.

18
00:02:58,670 --> 00:03:01,350
Carpenter's glue and a bit of patience.

19
00:03:03,550 --> 00:03:08,210
The front rack is glued at a 90 degree angle for us.

20
00:03:08,970 --> 00:03:16,790
It's desirable to keep to this angle so we wouldn't further have wobbles and curvatures of the central guide rotation axis.

21
00:03:17,870 --> 00:03:26,770
The rear rack is installed on the lower guide also at a 90 degree angle to its movement.

22
00:03:26,770 --> 00:03:34,730
Well, and here you can see I traced lines, that we also have a 90 degree angle here.

23
00:03:38,430 --> 00:03:45,930
The rear rack is also glued, but glued at this point.

24
00:03:47,130 --> 00:03:49,990
Here we have adjustment screws.

25
00:03:50,870 --> 00:03:56,010
The width of the rear rack of the machine — I planed it slightly.

26
00:03:56,010 --> 00:04:00,510
That's why it's 3 mm narrower than the main guide.

27
00:04:01,830 --> 00:04:06,490
And here certain gaps are visible from one side and the other.

28
00:04:07,170 --> 00:04:23,870
These gaps let me, by tightening these screws, set the support force on the lower guide so this rear rack could move with effort and wouldn't pop out.

29
00:04:23,870 --> 00:04:29,490
I fastened it to the lower guide at these holes with screws.

30
00:04:32,690 --> 00:04:38,370
This part seats on carpenter's glue, like these guide corners.

31
00:04:39,570 --> 00:04:46,530
The central rotation axis of the coil is a 6 mm stud with cut thread.

32
00:04:46,530 --> 00:04:54,130
The cut thread along its whole length lets you easily pick the needed distance for installing guide disks.

33
00:04:54,730 --> 00:05:00,910
The guide disks are also cut from solid plywood 9 mm thick.

34
00:05:01,430 --> 00:05:06,570
After the disk was cut, I drew it with compass help.

35
00:05:07,190 --> 00:05:12,630
All put on an axis, the axis clamped in a screwdriver and rotates.

36
00:05:12,630 --> 00:05:20,010
The edges passed with sandpaper, that way getting a clear geometric circle.

37
00:05:21,290 --> 00:05:33,510
And with sandpaper we fit these disks under the moment they enter the tube of the future Tesla coil frame with effort.

38
00:05:35,130 --> 00:05:37,210
This is how the build works assembled.

39
00:05:38,410 --> 00:05:49,810
Now I do the revolution number regulation with the help of the lab power supply, by changing the supply DC potential.

40
00:06:06,320 --> 00:06:10,020
Now let's move on to some small tricks.

41
00:06:10,280 --> 00:06:15,800
At the end I'll show how a Tesla transformer is wound on this machine.

42
00:06:15,800 --> 00:06:26,000
Before starting to wind wire, cut the frame of necessary length, according to the calculation of winding length on this frame.

43
00:06:26,600 --> 00:06:30,140
And make a hole through which the wire will pass.

44
00:06:30,320 --> 00:06:32,080
This will be the start of the winding.

45
00:06:32,200 --> 00:06:35,060
I made it at this point with awl help.

46
00:06:36,060 --> 00:06:43,780
After the hole is made, clean its top with a knife so there's an even surface.

47
00:06:45,860 --> 00:06:59,160
I recommend making the start hole a couple cm from the edge of the frame, so there's a distance for which it'd be convenient to fix the coil on the board.

48
00:07:00,800 --> 00:07:09,740
And now when the hole is made, we can move on to installing the guide disk.

49
00:07:10,620 --> 00:07:13,180
The front guide disk I've already fastened.

50
00:07:13,180 --> 00:07:17,640
And the rear guide disk is in a movable position.

51
00:07:18,440 --> 00:07:26,800
The rear guide disk we'll install so that this hole that was made is at the front.

52
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:34,560
After the guide disks are tightened, the coil frame is put in its place.

53
00:07:34,560 --> 00:07:49,800
The front guide disk is put practically at the edge of the coil frame, and the rear is sunk to a depth so the wire hole in the frame was behind it.

54
00:07:51,800 --> 00:07:53,380
I can demonstrate.

55
00:07:53,680 --> 00:07:57,500
The awl enters, and here is the tip.

56
00:07:57,580 --> 00:07:59,200
We'll pull the wire through here.

57
00:08:00,200 --> 00:08:02,300
Two unfastened nuts remain.

58
00:08:02,420 --> 00:08:07,160
This will support in the rear part of the machine rack.

59
00:08:08,700 --> 00:08:14,880
Now here is the moment of the stud that's the rotation axis and has a through hole.

60
00:08:15,460 --> 00:08:24,200
The same through hole is present in the transitional shaft made from a copper tube of corresponding diameter.

61
00:08:25,200 --> 00:08:42,580
When putting this shaft on the stud, the hole becomes coaxial and a cotter pin is lowered into the hole, this way preventing rotation of the coupling on the stud.

62
00:08:42,580 --> 00:08:55,640
The stud is round from this side, and from the opposite end I made a shape under the gearbox shaft.

63
00:08:57,060 --> 00:09:01,120
All made from 9 mm plywood.

64
00:09:01,520 --> 00:09:11,340
Here is a glued magnet that serves as the revolution sensor on the machine.

65
00:09:11,340 --> 00:09:14,040
It activates a reed switch.

66
00:09:14,800 --> 00:09:23,280
Now I installed the guide axis between the front support rack of the machine and the rear.

67
00:09:23,380 --> 00:09:37,400
The rear support rack is movable, it can move along the machine guide board, that way we can change the installation point under various frame lengths.

68
00:09:37,400 --> 00:09:43,440
I approximately made for myself a winding machine for coils of 80 cm length.

69
00:09:43,660 --> 00:09:45,840
This is quite enough for my needs.

70
00:09:46,540 --> 00:09:56,420
Also on the stud I installed a spacer tube that abuts this point.

71
00:09:57,300 --> 00:10:07,080
So the wood didn't break from the thread, I made a washer, seating it on two screws.

72
00:10:07,360 --> 00:10:17,480
The copper spacer tube abuts exactly into it, and then it abuts these spacer nuts.

73
00:10:18,140 --> 00:10:25,580
It's important to accurately strengthen the whole build so it didn't have play.

74
00:10:25,580 --> 00:10:31,680
Because when you're winding wire, if there's play, this will reflect in additional inconveniences.

75
00:10:32,320 --> 00:10:36,080
And so when pressed, the system works stably.

76
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:46,180
The rear support build of the machine is fastened to the guide with two screws.

77
00:10:47,400 --> 00:10:51,260
In the front and rear part and analogously from the opposite side.

78
00:10:51,260 --> 00:10:59,860
This way the build acquires rigidity and can be installed in all positions.

79
00:11:00,940 --> 00:11:05,040
Here I removed the play with nuts help.

80
00:11:06,060 --> 00:11:09,360
Now axial shift is absent.

81
00:11:10,720 --> 00:11:13,800
You can pay attention to how the reed switch works.

82
00:11:17,820 --> 00:11:22,380
When the magnet approaches, the reed switch contact attracts.

83
00:11:22,380 --> 00:11:26,000
And closes the system.

84
00:11:28,140 --> 00:11:39,520
The output of the reed switch through this adapter will be connected to a calculator.

85
00:11:40,060 --> 00:11:42,540
It'll count revolutions.

86
00:11:43,540 --> 00:11:46,920
I did the connection of the calculator to the reed switch.

87
00:11:46,920 --> 00:11:54,720
These two conductors going into the calculator are now connected on the board parallel to the contacts of the equals key.

88
00:11:55,420 --> 00:11:57,200
How does this work?

89
00:11:57,360 --> 00:12:03,200
Turn on the calculator and dial so it counts the revolution count for us.

90
00:12:03,580 --> 00:12:09,540
1 plus 1 and press equals.

91
00:12:12,360 --> 00:12:16,240
The calculator now switched to Grand Total mode.

92
00:12:16,960 --> 00:12:24,340
And at each press of the equals key, it'll add the last addend to the previous number.

93
00:12:24,440 --> 00:12:26,060
The last addend was 1.

94
00:12:26,380 --> 00:12:32,060
That way, we now at each press will sum plus 1.

95
00:12:33,540 --> 00:12:38,680
Now I turn on the system, apply power.

96
00:12:45,870 --> 00:12:56,890
And you see that on shaft rotation our calculator counts the revolution count.

97
00:13:05,460 --> 00:13:16,420
If I increase the supply voltage, the revolutions accelerate and the count goes faster.

98
00:13:18,700 --> 00:13:22,200
There's one more feature of using the calculator.

99
00:13:23,480 --> 00:13:30,720
For example, we're winding and our wire sharply went into overlap and we passed some turn count.

100
00:13:30,720 --> 00:13:34,300
And the system continues to count for us.

101
00:13:35,280 --> 00:13:45,080
Turn off power and remember the number of revolutions that was on the calculator.

102
00:13:45,360 --> 00:13:46,500
Now we have 46.

103
00:13:46,760 --> 00:13:48,100
Zero out the indicator.

104
00:13:49,660 --> 00:13:51,140
Now enter it again.

105
00:13:51,380 --> 00:13:52,140
46.

106
00:13:53,260 --> 00:13:54,360
Minus.

107
00:13:55,720 --> 00:13:58,040
And dial one.

108
00:14:03,040 --> 00:14:09,440
Now unwind the turn count manually back to the spool that went into overlap.

109
00:14:10,340 --> 00:14:14,780
And the calculator at that subtracts the turn count.

110
00:14:14,920 --> 00:14:17,280
I rotate now in manual mode.

111
00:14:17,380 --> 00:14:18,200
45.

112
00:14:19,460 --> 00:14:20,500
Unwind.

113
00:14:21,520 --> 00:14:22,500
44.

114
00:14:26,230 --> 00:14:32,830
Thus we unwind the defect that happened during winding.

115
00:14:36,490 --> 00:14:44,830
And further don't forget at the subsequent start of winding to switch the system back to summing mode.

116
00:14:45,470 --> 00:14:46,850
Repeat the same operation.

117
00:14:46,990 --> 00:14:48,190
Our 40 turns.

118
00:14:48,790 --> 00:14:51,270
Add one.

119
00:14:52,070 --> 00:14:59,010
And at subsequent system start the calculator will count in the larger direction.

120
00:15:01,210 --> 00:15:11,310
This is the important moment that we count the turn count the coil frame did for us.

121
00:15:11,370 --> 00:15:17,850
To know precisely the number of meters of wire that was laid on this frame.

122
00:15:17,850 --> 00:15:22,430
This will be useful at the moment of frequency fitting.

123
00:15:22,510 --> 00:15:26,850
Combining LC resonance frequency with the frequency of the wave on conductor length.

124
00:15:27,130 --> 00:15:36,650
An important addition to this machine's build is the frame on which the spool with winding wire will rotate.

125
00:15:37,510 --> 00:15:44,530
This is the simplest variant, made in a quick hand, but nevertheless its effectiveness doesn't decrease from this.

126
00:15:44,530 --> 00:15:56,750
The sense is in setting the spool so its lower cheeks rubbed against the lower surface of the board.

127
00:15:57,190 --> 00:16:01,910
That way, due to friction force, we provide a certain wire tension.

128
00:16:02,990 --> 00:16:04,570
Here it slips.

129
00:16:05,470 --> 00:16:11,910
The places where the spool frame rubs during rotation are visible.

130
00:16:12,910 --> 00:16:31,070
If this moment isn't provided, then it'll be very hard during winding wire to hold so the turns wouldn't go off, because you'd need to constantly use the second hand as a tensioning mechanism.

131
00:16:31,490 --> 00:16:35,410
And with such a method the process is much simpler.

132
00:16:35,410 --> 00:16:43,730
In the best case, of course, here on the build provide some additional friction, adjustable, but this is for the future.

133
00:16:44,450 --> 00:16:50,750
For now for winding a couple coils such a variant is quite working.

134
00:16:51,410 --> 00:16:57,790
Here I made holes for a plastic guide at a certain height needed by me.

135
00:16:58,830 --> 00:17:03,370
And this whole system performed quite well in work.

136
00:17:03,370 --> 00:17:10,790
Before starting to wind, the coil frame is dry-wiped if there's any contamination on the surface.

137
00:17:11,110 --> 00:17:17,570
Then the wire leads into the frame hole and bends in the opposite side from the winding direction.

138
00:17:18,630 --> 00:17:22,810
I fixed the conductor from inside the frame with sticky tape help.

139
00:17:23,780 --> 00:17:26,330
I fixed it in two places.

140
00:17:28,490 --> 00:17:33,350
It's visible that it's fixed.

141
00:17:34,350 --> 00:17:36,650
Now we can move to winding.

142
00:17:36,970 --> 00:17:43,530
The first meters will be hardest, until you form about tens of turns.

143
00:17:43,750 --> 00:17:50,730
Further you can increase the motor rotation speed and systematically wind.

144
00:17:51,730 --> 00:17:54,430
The spool with wire is installed on the floor.

145
00:17:55,310 --> 00:18:03,550
I install the machine itself at the edge of the table and do first wire revolutions manually on the frame.

146
00:18:04,290 --> 00:18:08,450
At that, don't forget to turn on the calculator for revolution counting.

147
00:18:08,910 --> 00:18:10,650
That's how this happens.

148
00:18:17,720 --> 00:18:24,120
Necessary to do about 4-5 turns.

149
00:18:25,120 --> 00:18:27,360
Pay attention that I dropped the wire.

150
00:18:27,360 --> 00:18:30,900
Nothing unwinds since the wire has certain tension.

151
00:18:31,620 --> 00:18:38,640
Now I shift the wire carefully along the coil axis.

152
00:18:39,680 --> 00:18:43,200
I form perpendicular direction to the frame.

153
00:18:43,860 --> 00:18:49,640
This is the most complex part of starting the winding work.

154
00:18:53,660 --> 00:18:56,660
Carefully do this work.

155
00:18:58,480 --> 00:19:02,580
And further everything will go much faster.

156
00:19:03,960 --> 00:19:06,720
The correct start of the wire is done.

157
00:19:07,420 --> 00:19:10,060
The calculator already counted 11 turns.

158
00:19:10,220 --> 00:19:15,880
And now at subsequent winding the conductor lays evenly.

159
00:19:16,880 --> 00:19:22,320
Now we can already move to winding in automatic mode.

160
00:19:24,800 --> 00:19:27,740
The order of automatic winding is like this.

161
00:19:28,900 --> 00:19:33,300
With the index fingernail of my left hand I hold the turns.

162
00:19:34,340 --> 00:19:37,520
And the right hand slightly leads the conductor.

163
00:19:38,180 --> 00:19:42,220
That way we do laying turn to turn.

164
00:19:42,220 --> 00:19:44,320
Now I apply power.

165
00:19:44,780 --> 00:19:47,440
First small potential.

166
00:19:47,540 --> 00:19:49,600
The motor here is at 24 volts.

167
00:19:49,980 --> 00:19:51,460
I apply about 9 volts.

168
00:19:52,060 --> 00:19:54,340
And then I can accelerate the rotation.

169
00:19:58,640 --> 00:20:00,720
Rotation slowly started.

170
00:20:01,720 --> 00:20:03,200
I hold.

171
00:20:05,240 --> 00:20:08,820
And increase the supply voltage.

172
00:20:18,680 --> 00:20:24,980
The winding happens in such a mode.

173
00:20:27,160 --> 00:20:34,680
As I do about 50 turns, I can increase the speed.

174
00:20:39,620 --> 00:20:40,420
Rotation.

175
00:20:42,620 --> 00:20:45,880
Because rigidity of the start already appears.

176
00:20:51,420 --> 00:20:54,680
I applied 20 V of power.

177
00:21:00,530 --> 00:21:03,810
Now the calculator already shows 60 turns.

178
00:21:04,970 --> 00:21:06,230
We managed to lay them.

179
00:21:13,730 --> 00:21:17,130
As they say — primitive but effective.

180
00:21:44,280 --> 00:21:51,660
Now I've laid 100 turns on the coil frame.

181
00:21:53,700 --> 00:21:56,040
Such came out the winding for us.

182
00:21:57,560 --> 00:22:01,100
The first turn we'll then carefully equalize.

183
00:22:02,480 --> 00:22:05,360
The calculator shows exactly 100 turns.

184
00:22:05,760 --> 00:22:07,640
What do I recommend doing now?

185
00:22:09,100 --> 00:22:10,460
A very important moment.

186
00:22:10,660 --> 00:22:14,300
Because in the winding process different things can happen.

187
00:22:15,220 --> 00:22:19,200
The wire will go into overlap or something else.

188
00:22:19,880 --> 00:22:25,200
Every 100 turns make a mark on the frame behind the conductor.

189
00:22:25,380 --> 00:22:26,800
And mark the turn count.

190
00:22:27,340 --> 00:22:36,540
That way if something happens to you, you can always unwind the conductor back to the coil spool.

191
00:22:36,800 --> 00:22:40,940
Reach the turn count point that was indicated for you here.

192
00:22:41,620 --> 00:22:47,340
And further go from the precise count point.

193
00:22:47,340 --> 00:22:51,240
Now I'll apply this marker mark.

194
00:22:59,340 --> 00:23:00,260
Like this.

195
00:23:01,140 --> 00:23:03,500
And sign.

196
00:23:04,740 --> 00:23:08,100
Here at this point we had 100 turns.

197
00:23:08,700 --> 00:23:11,400
Which the calculator shows us.

198
00:23:12,520 --> 00:23:13,590
Work finished.

199
00:23:14,080 --> 00:23:19,220
This whole coil winding operation took about 15 minutes.

200
00:23:19,320 --> 00:23:22,120
Turn count recorded here.

201
00:23:23,220 --> 00:23:25,820
By readings, 832 turns.

202
00:23:26,760 --> 00:23:30,300
And the edge of the wire is fixed with sticky tape help.

203
00:23:30,480 --> 00:23:33,500
Plus additionally 2 turns made.

204
00:23:33,920 --> 00:23:40,060
Now we can move on to painting the coil with the first layer of shellac.

205
00:23:40,800 --> 00:23:42,400
It'll fix the whole wire.

206
00:23:42,900 --> 00:23:46,180
It won't let it further unwind, go away.

207
00:23:46,280 --> 00:23:49,480
This is especially critical for coil edges.

208
00:23:51,820 --> 00:23:54,580
Varnishing is also a pleasure.

209
00:23:54,700 --> 00:23:59,480
DC motor and voltage regulation.

210
00:24:00,560 --> 00:24:02,780
I can regulate the revolution count.

211
00:24:02,940 --> 00:24:07,920
Of course you'll also need to make a foot pedal for this machine.

212
00:24:08,420 --> 00:24:14,240
Which will work as a PWM regulator in the system.

213
00:24:14,920 --> 00:24:17,780
And then it'll be absolute convenience.

214
00:24:18,590 --> 00:24:25,720
Before starting varnishing I passed it with napkin help.

215
00:24:25,820 --> 00:24:26,760
Remove dust.

216
00:24:30,280 --> 00:24:35,020
And now we can directly apply varnish.

217
00:24:35,100 --> 00:24:37,080
I'll apply with a small brush.

218
00:24:38,880 --> 00:24:39,680
Dip in varnish.

219
00:24:39,680 --> 00:24:40,400
Here.

220
00:24:41,900 --> 00:24:48,580
And with such a simple movement the varnish is applied.

221
00:24:48,800 --> 00:24:52,440
That is, you don't even need to apply effort.

222
00:24:53,160 --> 00:24:56,020
The varnish evenly distributes by turns.

223
00:25:08,340 --> 00:25:12,160
Such small mechanization is pleasant and convenient.

224
00:25:13,360 --> 00:25:19,740
Small coils of smaller diameters can of course be wound manually.

225
00:25:19,740 --> 00:25:26,060
But such, with 150 mm diameter, that's already extremely inconvenient.

226
00:25:26,720 --> 00:25:28,760
And the thin wire will be very long.

227
00:25:31,620 --> 00:25:44,120
Also with this method of applying varnish, after the whole coil is covered, leave it at slow rotation for 20 minutes.

228
00:25:44,760 --> 00:25:51,420
And this way the varnish distributes very evenly without drops.

229
00:25:53,720 --> 00:25:54,760
Convenient.

230
00:26:00,900 --> 00:26:04,300
Overall, this way I covered the whole coil.

231
00:26:07,500 --> 00:26:08,060
Here.

232
00:26:08,640 --> 00:26:10,520
One coil I already made.

233
00:26:12,560 --> 00:26:13,600
Covered with varnish.

234
00:26:15,640 --> 00:26:18,000
Here is the second, the same.

235
00:26:22,160 --> 00:26:23,660
Covered with one layer.

